 at the intersection of literature, sex, gender, and postmodernism. Illustrating how the generational conflict between the lesbian- feminists of twenty years ago and the queer theorists of today stokes the critical fires of contemporary lesbian and literary theory, Heterosexual Plots and Lesbian Narratives concludes by arguing for a broad and generous definition of lesbian writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aAmerican literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aEnglish literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHeterosexuality in literature. 0aHomosexuality and literaturexEnglish-speaking countries. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezEnglish-speaking countries. 0aLesbiansxIntellectual lifexEnglish-speaking countries. 0aLesbianszEnglish-speaking countriesxIntellectual life. 0aLesbians' writings, AmericanxHistory and criticismxEnglish-speaking countries. 0aLesbians' writings, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aLesbians' writings, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aMan-woman relationships in literature. 0aNarration (Rhetoric) 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aSex role in literature. 0aWomen and literaturexHistoryx20th centuryxEnglish-speaking countries. 0aWomen and literaturezEnglish-speaking countriesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814728840423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814728840.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter